<subSubSection id="95D13DD79A913AF6FA460F90035BAED5" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="E960297711CBE9E1649E1E01BEF07DFA" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="821A12D266CD04D8E985C8BCC40E103A" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">
Female of this species similar to that of 
<taxonomicName id="2D46A344A3FDD7792935F9CCC5B27912" genus="O." lsidName="O. bhutanica" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="bhutanica">
<emphasis id="F1650B773ED74BF7928C7E158E890B99" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">O. bhutanica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Ono, 2001 and 
<taxonomicName id="4D696C506C3E5FE7D90A1CCE7B15A88F" genus="O." lsidName="O. mucunica" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="mucunica">
<emphasis id="3322977A4A0C2BDD93B0A424D9F3B2B5" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">O. mucunica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. in having vulva with M-shaped pattern formed by copulatory ducts (
<emphasis id="0225146766C854A896915FB02C68058A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">CD</emphasis>
) and spermathecae (
<emphasis id="A512E13871A921D238C4B1D6DADC11EF" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">SP</emphasis>
), but differs from both species by the copulatory openings (
<emphasis id="D2BF16F5DA986399751EA30272C10510" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">CO</emphasis>
) oriented outwards (vs. inwards or anteriorly) and copulatory ducts (
<emphasis id="21995F7C27983480B5F5284CCC590845" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">CD</emphasis>
) 2 
<normalizedToken id="C9E7B9BA3576BC39C980B1FB383CA846" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
thinner than spermathecae (
<emphasis id="E4D9ABEB4CDAADF43B7C06E3E3FB7BEF" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">SP</emphasis>
) (vs. equal in size) (cf. Fig. 
<figureCitation id="6A57C3FB8B768F6B3B099AAAE3523E97" captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Oxytate bicornis Liu, Liu &amp; Xu, 2017, female. A habitus, dorsal view B same, ventral view C epigyne, ventral view D same, dorsal view. Abbreviations: CD - copulatory duct, CO - copulatory opening, FD - fertilisation duct, P - pocket, SP - spermatheca. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (A, B), 0.1 mm (C, D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.72829.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/672170" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">8C, D</figureCitation>
vs. Fig. 
<figureCitation id="FDC6943E5D9F26B1A7C922C873410848" captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figure 10. Oxytate mucunica sp. nov., female. A habitus, dorsal view B same, ventral view C epigyne, ventral view D same, dorsal view. Abbreviations: CD - copulatory duct, CO - copulatory opening, FD - fertilisation duct, SP - spermatheca. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (A, B), 0.1 mm (C, D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.72829.figure10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/672172" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">10C, D</figureCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="1FE21498D7B023513971691AA0E2F8AA" author="Ono, H" journalOrPublisher="Entomologica Basiliensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" pagination="203 - 236" refId="B13" refString="Ono, H, 2001. Crab spiders of the family Thomisidae from the Kingdom of Bhutan (Arachnida, Araneae). Entomologica Basiliensis 23: 203 - 236" title="Crab spiders of the family Thomisidae from the Kingdom of Bhutan (Arachnida, Araneae)." volume="23" year="2001">Ono 2001</bibRefCitation>
: figs 4, 5). Male of 
<taxonomicName id="CECC1C7B2CCFFA27CC86954AFBE9E7EE" genus="O." lsidName="O. bicornis" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="bicornis">
<emphasis id="EE3EB197BDA8923F77D57EC0BC43FDB4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">O. bicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles those of 
<taxonomicName id="BCC7199098E2EA70E356D4AB1871DFAC" genus="O." lsidName="O. bhutanica" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="bhutanica">
<emphasis id="5CED22B5D000C357E33C9E98C54D73B3" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">O. bhutanica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having spine-like embolus (
<emphasis id="E3181B238CEBDBC33DAED887BB8DA5D3" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">E</emphasis>
) and moderately long retrolateral tibial apophysis (
<emphasis id="5D9F872687F89448E7607E775D42E527" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">RTA</emphasis>
), reaching to the middle of the cymbium but can be distinguished by the bifurcated retrolateral tibial apophysis (vs. horn-like) (cf. Fig. 
<figureCitation id="CA31C0C21D14B2F12701D4196CFF2EB9" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Oxytate bicornis Liu, Liu &amp; Xu, 2017, male. A habitus, dorsal view B palp, ventral view C same, prolateral view D same, retrolateral view. Abbreviations: E - embolus, RTA - retrolateral tibial apophysis, SD - sperm duct, TR - tegular ridge, VTA - ventral tibial apophysis. Scale bars: 1 mm (A), 0.5 mm (B-D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.72829.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/672171" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">9B-D</figureCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="64B67C8B37EBDC0849C4D20EC7F9C490" author="Ono, H" journalOrPublisher="Entomologica Basiliensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" pagination="203 - 236" refId="B13" refString="Ono, H, 2001. Crab spiders of the family Thomisidae from the Kingdom of Bhutan (Arachnida, Araneae). Entomologica Basiliensis 23: 203 - 236" title="Crab spiders of the family Thomisidae from the Kingdom of Bhutan (Arachnida, Araneae)." volume="23" year="2001">Ono 2001</bibRefCitation>
: figs 2, 3).
</paragraph>
<caption id="E8F15956BD80E8F9F3B88DBDC472E794" doi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.72829.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/672170" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" start="Figure 8" startId="F8">
